eek --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eek.gif ALT=":eek"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :x --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/sick.gif ALT=":x"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#00CC00><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bmrcliffordsenglishclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=teruin2pac>TeruiN2pac</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#00CC00>(2/13/03 10:54:14 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fmrcliffordsenglishclassesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  addition </span><hr size=1> When Joe was pressured in the factory, it was his instincts that told him to just keep up with it. He thought he could maybe make a new batch to replace the cracked cylinder heads. I don't think it was so evil of him to do such a thing. Worse things could have happened. At least he felt bad about his mistake. When Chris wanted to marry Ann, I think that it would have been thoughtful of Chris to ask his mother for permission and be patient with her. It was his right to marry her, but he was killing his mothers dream of Larry returning. But again I don't believe it portrays American society more than any other affluent society. Money does cause corruption, which caused Joe to ignore his conscious. <br>
