hclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=meckeljp>meckeljp</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#00CC00>(2/13/03 10:06:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fmrcliffordsenglishclassesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Does AMS accurately characterize American society?</span><hr size=1>      I believe that the play All My sons is a relatively accurate portrayl of American society today, at least moralistically.  However I dont think that it necessarily means that Americans are immoral, and only look out for themselves.  Joe Keller was a man trying to fend for his family, he wasn't trying to kill people.  He figured the heads would never be used, and by the time they were discovered he would have the factory working again.  I think that if this play accurately depicts Americans today, then yes we have problems, but in the end mean well.  For every Joe there is a Chris, a person that is absolutely opposed to hurting other people, no matter what.  Besides, I believe that Joe didn't have harmful intentions, just as most Americans today.  Society as a whole has good intentions, just the wrong way of doing things.  Joe was only trying to provide for his family, he had good intentions.  He just didn't think about different ways to do it,  made a bad decision,  and now men are dead because of it. Good intentions, with poor execution.  Americans sometimes become so obsessed with what they think they need to do, that they dont stop and look at what they're doing.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :hat --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/pimp.gif ALT=":hat"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCC99><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bmrcliffordsenglishclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=deanp2>deanp2</A></span><